And the wall collapsed...
Here's a quiz for history buffs: twenty years ago, 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4.
Which one do you remember best, and which had the greatest consequence for the planet?
a) The bloody repression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few answered c).
Because the events in Beijing and Khomeini's death, which made headlines, eclipsed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarność in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
However, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and consequently to the redefinition of the post-war international order.
There will be all sorts of commemoration of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many, it was an hour of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins remain unclear.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the beginning, we realize that the process was long and complex.
The Polish election was a point of no return, the moment where the movement in favor of change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader in charge of Poland, General Jaruzelski, concluded that the country's economic problems were too severe for him to tackle alone.
Why not turn to the Polish opposition, he asked - if not to find a solution, at least to share the responsibility for the situation?
After six months of negotiations, he达成协议：将举行自由和平等的立法选举，允许Solidarność参与。
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarność) never considered for a moment that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they never imagined they would be chased from power.
However, that is what happened.
Retrospectively, it is surprising that there were any doubts.
Solidarity campaigned boldly.
A famous poster parody, that of a classic Western movie titled "The Train Whistles Three Times," enjoyed great success: it shows Gary Cooper holding a ballot instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4 was the day of reckoning.
On this bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving birth to summer, voters sent the Polish communists packing.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one final perverse act that turned into an involuntary humiliation.
They designed a voting system where instead of choosing the candidates they wanted, the Poles had to cross off the names of those they did not want - essentially, all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere one looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had been waiting for, revenge against December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarność, and imprisoned its leaders.
The revolution with the pen!
Mastered with style, the pen that ultimately triumphs over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Some voters were tearing their ballots to shreds, thus decisively decapitating the old regime with an effective stroke.
Others savored the moment, perhaps lighting a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"He put my cousin in prison," snort!, "Look, this apparatchik got rich off our shortages," snort!
snort!
The communist campaign, however, went almost unnoticed.
In all of Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most relied on their monopoly in the media to get their message across: "Vote Lezek, a good communist."
One can credit the regime with recognizing its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party leaders to declare to them: "Our defeat is total; we need to find a political solution."
It meant that he wanted neither violence nor rigging, and the communists would have to live with the election result.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe knew that Solidarność would win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern bloc.
The Polish election was extremely encouraging for anticommunists around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what seemed impossible just a few days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began to dismantle the barbed wire erected along the border with Austria - a hole in the iron curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European House" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously acknowledged: "We saw nothing coming."
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom burst forth.
